      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under validated installation; FDA in-house FEA code under version-controlled repository with regression test suite. Required level 2: documented QA procedures and version control.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under formal software quality management systems. Ansys is a commercially validated solver; FDA code maintained under Git with CI regression testing against analytical benchmarks. Achieved level 3 reflects documented validation of the solver installation and traceability of all analysis files."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions executed for each solver; results within 1% of analytical values for beam bending and contact patch problems.",
      "rationale": "Each of the three modeling teams executed standard ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems prior to the F1717 analyses. Cantilever beam bending and Hertzian contact benchmarks confirmed solver accuracy within 0.6% and 0.9% respectively. Code verification is therefore satisfied at level 3 across the ensemble."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study conducted; QoI change between successive refinements < 2% at final mesh density. Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization error.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities evaluated for each modeling team. Richardson extrapolation yielded estimated discretization errors of 0.8–1.4% for stiffness, 1.1–1.7% for yield force, and 1.3–1.9% for force at 40 mm. All values below the 2% threshold. Final mesh selected based on convergence criterion informed by UQ sensitivity rankings identifying screw-rod contact region as highest-sensitivity zone."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence tolerances set to force residual < 1e-4 and displacement residual < 1e-5; Newton-Raphson iteration confirmed to converge within 25 iterations per load step.",
      "rationale": "All analyses used tight convergence tolerances consistent with ASME V&V 10 guidance. Load stepping verified to produce path-independent results for the nonlinear contact problem. No solution divergence observed across 33 model runs (3 teams × 11 constructs)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst not involved in original model construction; checklist-based verification of boundary conditions, material assignments, and load application.",
      "rationale": "Each team's model was independently reviewed by a second qualified analyst using a structured checklist covering geometry, material properties, contact definitions, boundary conditions, and load application. No critical use errors identified. Minor discrepancies in rod pre-tension specification were resolved prior to final analysis runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification provided for constitutive model selection (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V); contact formulation appropriate for screw-rod interface; geometric nonlinearity enabled for large-displacement regime.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening material model selected based on published Ti-6Al-4V stress-strain data and validated against coupon tension tests. Augmented Lagrangian contact formulation used for screw-rod interface, appropriate for the frictional sliding regime encountered during bending. Geometric nonlinearity (NLGEOM) enabled consistent with ASTM F1717 large-displacement loading protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from traceable coupon testing of the same material lot used in bench constructs; geometric dimensions from CMM measurement of physical screws and rods.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.2 GPa) derived from coupon tension tests on material from the same lot as the test constructs. Rod and screw dimensions verified by coordinate measuring machine. Friction coefficient range (0.12–0.18) from literature and confirmed as non-dominant by UQ sensitivity analysis, supporting use of nominal value 0.15 in the primary analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 constructs; constructs assembled from production-representative components; dimensional inspection of all constructs prior to testing.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs assembled from production-representative components by trained technicians following the device IFU. All constructs dimensionally inspected by CMM prior to testing; no construct exceeded dimensional tolerance. Constructs distributed across two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of physiologically relevant loading rates and temperatures; at minimum two distinct test conditions evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single loading rate (5 mm/min) and ambient temperature (23°C) per ASTM F1717. Physiological loading rates and in vivo temperature (37°C) were not evaluated. This factor achieves level 2 (single standardized condition documented) but falls short of the required level 3. This known gap is acknowledged; the COU is limited to ASTM F1717 standard test conditions and the device is not intended for dynamic fatigue prediction from this model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to experimental construct configurations; traceability documented for each construct-model pairing.",
      "rationale": "Each of the 11 FEA models was parameterized using the CMM-measured dimensions and coupon-derived material properties for the corresponding physical construct. Construct-specific assembly torque was recorded and translated to rod pre-tension in the model. Traceability matrix linking each physical construct to its FEA counterpart is included in the validation package appendix."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval computed for each QoI; acceptance threshold E/uval < 1.96; mean absolute percentage error < 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 5 for all three QoIs across all 11 constructs and three modeling teams. Maximum E/uval observed was 1.61 (force at 40 mm, DePuy Synthes team). All values below 1.96 threshold. Mean absolute errors: stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 7.9% — all below 10% threshold. Comparison plots and tabulated results included in validation report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) directly correspond to the regulatory submission endpoints and clinical performance metrics for pedicle screw constructs under ASTM F1717.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are the primary endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly cited in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. Stiffness characterizes construct rigidity relevant to fusion mechanics; yield force and force at 40 mm bound the failure envelope. QoI relevance is therefore high, achieving level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation constructs use the same device design, material lot, and test standard as the intended COU; validation loading conditions bracket the COU loading scenario.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs are the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw — identical to the device under evaluation. Same material lot, same assembly procedure, same ASTM F1717 test protocol. The COU is explicitly bounded to ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, which is precisely the validation scenario. Relevance is therefore direct and complete at level 3."
    }
